Creating a PHP utility class for MIME type detection and file upload enforcement can be useful in web applications to ensure that uploaded files meet certain criteria. Below is an example of such a class:

```php
<?php

class FileUploader
{
    private $allowedMimeTypes = ['image/jpeg', 'image/png', 'application/pdf'];
    private $maxFileSize = 5 * 1024 * 1024; // 5MB

    public function upload($file, $destination)
    {
        // Check if the file was uploaded successfully
        if (!isset($_FILES[$file]) || $_FILES[$file]['error'] !== UPLOAD_ERR_OK) {
            throw new Exception("File upload failed.");
        }

        // Get file details
        $fileTmpName = $_FILES[$file]['tmp_name'];
        $fileName = basename($_FILES[$file]['name']);
        $fileSize = $_FILES[$file]['size'];

        // Check if the file is within allowed size
        if ($fileSize > $this->maxFileSize) {
            throw new Exception("File size exceeds maximum allowed size.");
        }

        // Get the MIME type of the uploaded file
        $fileMimeType = mime_content_type($fileTmpName);

        // Check if the MIME type is in the allowed list
        if (!in_array($fileMimeType, $this->allowedMimeTypes)) {
            throw new Exception("Invalid file type.");
        }

        // Move the uploaded file to the destination directory
        if (!move_uploaded_file($fileTmpName, $destination . DIRECTORY_SEPARATOR . $fileName)) {
            throw new Exception("Failed to move uploaded file.");
        }

        return $destination . DIRECTORY_SEPARATOR . $fileName;
    }
}

