### Step 2: Register the Custom Post Type

Add the following code to your theme’s `functions.php` file (or in a custom plugin):

```php
function register_api_response_cache() {
    $labels = array(
        'name'               => __('API Responses', 'your-textdomain'),
        'singular_name'      => __('API Response', 'your-textdomain'),
        'menu_name'          => __('API Responses', 'your-textdomain'),
        'add_new'            => __('Add New API Response', 'your-textdomain'),
        'add_new_item'       => __('Add New API Response', 'your-textdomain'),
        'edit_item'           => __('Edit API Response', 'your-textdomain'),
        'new_item'            => __('New API Response', 'your-textdomain'),
        'view_item'           => __('View API Response', 'your-textdomain'),
        'search_items'       => __('Search API Responses', 'your-textdomain'),
        'not_found'          => __('No API Responses found', 'your-textdomain'),
        'not_found_in_trash' => __('No API Responses found in Trash', 'your-textdomain'),
    );

    $args = array(
        'label'                 => __('API Responses', 'your-textdomain'),
        'description'            => __('Store and reuse API responses.', 'your-textdomain'),
        'labels'                => $labels,
        'supports'              => array('title', 'editor'),
        'public'               => true,
        'has_archive'           => true,
        'menu_position'         => 5,
        'show_ui'              => true,
        'show_in_menu'          => true,
        'can_export'            => true,
    );

    register_post_type('api_response', $args);
}

add_action('init', 'register_api_response_cache');
```

### Step 3: Fetch and Store API Responses

You can use WordPress’ `wp_insert_post()` function to create a new post of the `api_response` type. Here’s an example of how you might fetch data from an external API and store it in this custom post type:

```php
function save_api_response() {
    // Example: Fetch data from an API
    $api_url = 'https://api.example.com/data';
    $response = wp_remote_get($api_url);

    if (is_wp_error($response)) {
        return;
    }

    $data = json_decode(wp_remote_retrieve_body($response), true);

    // Create a new post in the 'api_response' type
    $post_id = wp_insert_post(array(
        'post_type'    => 'api_response',
        'post_title'   => 'API Response ' . date('Y-m-d H:i:s'),
        'post_content'  => json_encode($data),
        'status'       => 'publish',
    ));

    if ($post_id > 0) {
        // Optionally, you can add meta data or other properties here
        update_post_meta($post_id, '_api_response_data', $data);
    }
}

add_action('wp_insert_post', 'save_api_response');
```

### Step 4: Retrieve Cached API Responses

You can retrieve cached API responses using the `get_posts()` function. This example retrieves all published posts of type `api_response`:

```php
function get_cached_api_responses() {
    $args = array(
        'post_type' => 'api_response',
        'posts_per_page' => -1, // Get all results
        'status'     => 'publish',
    );

    $query = new WP_Query($args);

    if ($query->have_posts()) {
        while ($query->have_posts()) {
            $query->the_post();
            echo '<h2>' . get_the_title() . '</h2>';
            echo '<pre>' . esc_html(get_the_content()) . '</pre>';
        }
    } else {
        echo 'No API responses found.';
    }

    wp_reset_postdata(); // Reset post data to avoid conflicts
}

add_action('wp_footer', 'get_cached_api_responses');
