To create a CSV data parser and generator in Node.js using streams, we can use the built-in `stream` module provided by Node.js. This allows us to process large files efficiently without loading them into memory.

Firstly, let's define a CSV parser stream:

```javascript
const { Transform } = require('stream');

class CsvParser extends Transform {
  constructor(options) {
    super(options);
    this.rowCount = 0;
    this.columnHeaders = [];
  }

  _transform(chunk, encoding, callback) {
    const rows = chunk.toString().split('\n');
    for (let i = 0; i < rows.length; i++) {
      if (i === 0) {
        this.columnHeaders = rows[i].split(',');
      } else {
        const row = rows[i].split(',');
        this.rowCount++;
        this.push(row);
      }
    }
    callback();
  }

  getRowCount() {
    return this.rowCount;
  }

  getColumnHeaders() {
    return this.columnHeaders;
  }
}
```

In the above code, we define a `CsvParser` class that extends `Transform`. This class will parse CSV data from an input stream and output parsed rows as an array of strings. It also maintains state about the row count and column headers.

To use the parser, you can create an instance of it and pipe your input stream through it:

```javascript
const fs = require('fs');
const csvParser = new CsvParser({ objectMode: true });

fs.createReadStream('input.csv')
  .pipe(csvParser)
  .on('data', row => {
    console.log(row);
  })
  .on('finish', () => {
    console.log(`Parsed ${csvParser.getRowCount()} rows with headers: ${csvParser.getColumnHeaders()}`);
  });
```

In the above code, we create a file stream that reads from `input.csv`. We then pipe this stream through our `CsvParser` instance. For each row parsed by the parser, it logs the row to the console. Once all rows have been processed, it logs the total number of rows and the column headers.

Now, let's define a CSV generator stream:

```javascript
class CsvGenerator extends Transform {
  constructor(options) {
    super(options);
    this.columns = options.columns;
  }

  _transform(chunk, encoding, callback) {
    const rowValues = chunk.map(value => value || '');
    const row = rowValues.join(',');
    this.push(row + '\n');
    callback();
  }
}

// Example usage:
const csvGenerator = new CsvGenerator({ columns: ['id', 'name', 'email'] });

csvGenerator.write(['1', 'John Doe', 'john.doe@example.com']);
csvGenerator.write(['2', 'Jane Smith', 'jane.smith@example.com']);
csvGenerator.end();

csvGenerator.on('data', chunk => {
  console.log(chunk);
});
```

In the above code, we define a `CsvGenerator` class that extends `Transform`. This class will generate CSV data from an input stream and output lines of CSV data. It requires a list of column names in its constructor.

To use the generator, you can create an instance of it and write rows to it using the `write()` method. When all rows have been written, you call the `end()` method:

```javascript
